Governor Ahmadu Fintiri has pledged to pay N33 minimum wage to local government workers in Adamawa state. Fintiri at a town hall meeting Friday to mark democracy day, vowed that, the new minimum wage is aimed at strengthening dividends of democracy and governance at the grassroots. He added a lot of reforms have been revived, such as the reintroduction of for promotion examination into the office of permanent secretary, to bring sanity among workers in the state. He also revealed that,  counterpart funding for Universal Basic Education (UBE), emoluments for the year 2016, 2017, 2018 and 2019 has been paid,  while process for accessing 2020 grant has been completed. The sum of N10.5m monthly is been paid for purchase of learning and instructional materials for public schools, inline with the free education for all policy of the PDP-led administration. Construction of over 300 km rural roads is ongoing, in addition over 18.3 km of new ones within the state capital which is at various stages of completion. Dr Umar Garba-Pella, Commissioner of Information and Strategy, further added that the town hall meeting will next hold in Mubi and Ganye respectively. 